Introduction to the 3D Schwarzschild White Hole Model
Core Concept
This visualization simulates curved spacetime around a Schwarzschild black hole using a unique approach: employing the inverse of the metric coefficient (1/α) to map and highlight the structure of spacetime.

The Schwarzschild Metric Coefficient
In Schwarzschild spacetime, the metric coefficient is:

text
α² = 1 - 2GM/(r c²)
Where:

r: radial distance from the center

M: mass of the object

G: gravitational constant

c: speed of light

Why Use 1/α?
Using the inverse of α instead of α provides several advantages:

Emphasizes the horizon: As r → r_s (Schwarzschild radius), α → 0, so 1/α → ∞. This makes the event horizon dramatically visible as regions where the grid lines "blow up" to infinity.

Reveals asymptotic regions: The colored segments (Regions 1-4) show where |1/α| ≥ 2, highlighting zones where spacetime curvature becomes extreme.

Enables folded mapping: When R < r_s, the folding technique maps different radial intervals onto the same physical space, allowing visualization of multiple asymptotic regions simultaneously.

What You See
Black grid lines: The neutral spacetime fabric, distorted by gravity but visible everywhere

Colored segments: Four asymptotic regions showing where 1/α approaches infinity:

Orange (Region 1): Outside → Event Horizon (∞ at H)

Purple (Region 2): Event Horizon → Singularity (∞ at S)

Blue (Region 3): Singularity → Event Horizon (∞ at H)

Green (Region 4): Event Horizon → Outside → Infinity

Blue sphere: The physical radius R marker

Red dashed sphere: The event horizon r_s = 2GM/c²

White Hole Mode
When enabled, the colored asymptotic segments are shown only in the upper half (z ≥ 0), revealing the white hole structure—a time-reversed version of the black hole where matter emerges from the singularity.

Interactive Controls
Mass Slider: Adjust the black hole mass (0.1-20 solar masses)

Radius Slider: Change the physical radius R

Checkboxes: Toggle visibility of spheres, grid lines, arrows, and white hole mode

Region Checkboxes: Select which asymptotic regions to display

This visualization helps build intuition about how spacetime curvature behaves near black holes and how mathematical transformations like 1/α can reveal hidden structures in general relativity.

